<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="579" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,259,1402]" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,331,357]" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is a patronym given in honor of my friend, Vasiliy V. Sergeev (
<collectingRegion box="[1291,1433,331,357]" country="Russia" name="Novosibirsk" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">Novosibirsk</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,230,367,394]" name="Russia" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">Russia</collectingCountry>
), who helped in spider collection and in organization of the field trip to Borus Mt. Range, where the 
<typeStatus box="[1338,1436,367,393]" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">holotype</typeStatus>
of this new species was collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="579" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,259,1402]" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,439,465]" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new species is similar to the Siberian species 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Marusik" baseAuthorityYear="1993" box="[886,1004,439,465]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Acantholycosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="12" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sterneri">
<emphasis box="[886,1004,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">A. sterneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as well as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Levi &amp; Levi" baseAuthorityYear="1951" box="[1126,1247,439,465]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Acantholycosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="12" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="solituda">
<emphasis box="[1126,1247,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">A. solituda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from the Rocky Mountains (
<collectingCountry box="[289,351,475,501]" name="United States of America" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">USA</collectingCountry>
). All three species share the following features: palea (
<emphasis box="[989,1014,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">Pl</emphasis>
) with a prominent extension (
<emphasis box="[1366,1396,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">Pe</emphasis>
) in the terminal part and the triangle shaped projection (
<emphasis box="[747,771,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">Ts</emphasis>
) on its posterior edge, strong terminal apophysis (
<emphasis box="[1342,1369,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">Ta</emphasis>
) with bifurcate tip and thick, cotton-like pubescence on legs I and II. 
<taxonomicName authority="Fomichev, 2021" authorityName="Fomichev" authorityYear="2021" box="[899,1166,547,573]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Acantholycosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="12" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sergeevi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[899,1166,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">Acantholycosa sergeevi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1177,1244,547,573]" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1177,1244,547,573]" pageId="12" pageNumber="579" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
differs from the both aforementioned species by the more developed and pointed triangle shaped projection on the posterior edge of the palea (cf. 
<figureCitation box="[337,463,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURES 32–43" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1742,1766]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,189,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-33@6.[151,1437,181,1719]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 32–43. Tegulum and subtegulum (32–37), bulb (38–40) and embolic division (41–43) of Acantholycosa sayanensis (32–33), A. sidorovi sp. n. (34–35), A. levinae (36–37) and A. sergeevi sp. n. (38–43). 32, 34, 36, 38, 41—ventral; 33, 35, 37, 39, 42—anterior; 40, 43—retrolateral. Scale bars=0.2 mm. Abbreviations: Aa apical arm of the tegular apophysis, Ba basal arm of the tegular apophysis, Em embolus, Pe extension of the palea, Pl palea, Ta terminal apophysis, Tg tegular apophysis, Ts triangle-shaped projection of the palea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5300798" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5300798/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">Figs 41–42</figureCitation>
and fig 3, 7 in 
<bibRefCitation author="Kronestedt, T. &amp; Marusik, Y. M." box="[638,960,619,645]" pageId="12" pageNumber="579" pagination="63 - 71" refId="ref10150" refString="Kronestedt, T. &amp; Marusik, Y. M. (2002) On Acantholycosa solituda (Levi &amp; Levi) and A. sterneri (Marusik) (Araneae: Lycosidae), a pair of geographically distant allied species. Acta Arachnologica, 51 (1), 63 - 71. https: // doi. org / 10.2476 / asjaa. 51.63" type="journal article" year="2002">Kronestedt &amp; Marusik 2002</bibRefCitation>
). The new species can be differed from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Marusik" baseAuthorityYear="1993" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Acantholycosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="12" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sterneri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">A. sterneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the terminal part of the palea less extended, the embolus (
<emphasis box="[917,954,656,681]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">Em</emphasis>
) directed at 2:30 o’clock (vs. 3:30 o’clock) and by the almost straight anterior edge of the tegular apophysis (
<emphasis box="[907,937,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">Tg</emphasis>
) (vs. triangular, cf. 
<figureCitation box="[1167,1298,691,717]" captionStart="FIGURES 32–43" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1742,1766]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,189,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-33@6.[151,1437,181,1719]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 32–43. Tegulum and subtegulum (32–37), bulb (38–40) and embolic division (41–43) of Acantholycosa sayanensis (32–33), A. sidorovi sp. n. (34–35), A. levinae (36–37) and A. sergeevi sp. n. (38–43). 32, 34, 36, 38, 41—ventral; 33, 35, 37, 39, 42—anterior; 40, 43—retrolateral. Scale bars=0.2 mm. Abbreviations: Aa apical arm of the tegular apophysis, Ba basal arm of the tegular apophysis, Em embolus, Pe extension of the palea, Pl palea, Ta terminal apophysis, Tg tegular apophysis, Ts triangle-shaped projection of the palea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5300798" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5300798/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">Figs 38, 41</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1312,1340,691,717]" captionStart="FIGURES 44–53" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1794,1818]" captionTargetBox="[163,1427,188,1770]" captionTargetId="figure-15@7.[151,1436,181,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 44–53. Tegulum and subtegulum (44–45, 52–53), bulb (46–48) and embolic division (49–51) of Acantholycosa sergeevi sp. n. (44–45) and Mongolicosa lizae sp. n. (46–53). 44, 46, 49, 52—ventral; 45, 47, 50, 53—anterior; 48, 51— retrolateral. Scale bars=0.2 mm. Abbreviations: Aa apical arm of the tegular apophysis, Ba basal arm of the tegular apophysis, Em embolus, Pl palea, Sd sperm duct, Ta terminal apophysis, Tg tegular apophysis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5300800" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5300800/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">44</figureCitation>
and fig. 
<quantity box="[151,195,727,754]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.778" pageId="12" pageNumber="579" unit="in" value="7.0">7 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Kronestedt, T. &amp; Marusik, Y. M." box="[203,526,727,753]" pageId="12" pageNumber="579" pagination="63 - 71" refId="ref10150" refString="Kronestedt, T. &amp; Marusik, Y. M. (2002) On Acantholycosa solituda (Levi &amp; Levi) and A. sterneri (Marusik) (Araneae: Lycosidae), a pair of geographically distant allied species. Acta Arachnologica, 51 (1), 63 - 71. https: // doi. org / 10.2476 / asjaa. 51.63" type="journal article" year="2002">Kronestedt &amp; Marusik 2002</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Fomichev, 2021" authorityName="Fomichev" authorityYear="2021" box="[545,810,727,753]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Acantholycosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="12" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sergeevi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[545,810,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">Acantholycosa sergeevi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[818,882,727,753]" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[818,882,727,753]" pageId="12" pageNumber="579" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Levi &amp; Levi" baseAuthorityYear="1951" box="[1191,1313,727,753]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Acantholycosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="12" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="solituda">
<emphasis box="[1191,1313,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">A. solituda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by thinner embolus (in anterior view) and by a straight basal arm (
<emphasis box="[783,814,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">Ba</emphasis>
) of the tegular apophysis (vs. bent posteriorly, cf. 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 32–43" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1742,1766]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,189,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-33@6.[151,1437,181,1719]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 32–43. Tegulum and subtegulum (32–37), bulb (38–40) and embolic division (41–43) of Acantholycosa sayanensis (32–33), A. sidorovi sp. n. (34–35), A. levinae (36–37) and A. sergeevi sp. n. (38–43). 32, 34, 36, 38, 41—ventral; 33, 35, 37, 39, 42—anterior; 40, 43—retrolateral. Scale bars=0.2 mm. Abbreviations: Aa apical arm of the tegular apophysis, Ba basal arm of the tegular apophysis, Em embolus, Pe extension of the palea, Pl palea, Ta terminal apophysis, Tg tegular apophysis, Ts triangle-shaped projection of the palea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5300798" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5300798/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="579">Figs 42</figureCitation>
, 
